00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:35.419
What is A-B testing?

00:02:35.419 --> 00:02:40.940
So let's say we have a user, Linda, and Linda logs on to Datacamp one day, and she's interested

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:42.600
in learning deep learning.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:47.080
So Linda could maybe see this page, and that's one of our course pages.

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:51.399
There's about a 50% chance of this if we're running an A-B test on it.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:53.320
But she also could have seen this page.

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:57.000
So you might notice there are a couple differences here, right, the color, but a big one is that

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.119
registration form that's now on the page.

00:02:59.119 --> 00:03:04.679
So what A-B testing is is randomly assigning visitors to your website to one or two or

00:03:04.679 --> 00:03:06.360
more experiences.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:09.860
Sometimes it involves changes on the page here.

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:13.800
Sometimes it's things like changes to a search algorithm or making the page faster.

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:17.800
But the idea is that by randomly assigning people and, you know, running these conditions

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:21.460
at the same time, you're controlling for all the other factors.

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:25.919
So this lets you know that if you see a difference between the control and the treatment group

00:03:25.919 --> 00:03:29.960
and you've run everything properly, any behavioral difference should be because of your change.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:35.320
And then you can be really confident it's had the impact you hoped it would.

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:38.520
Life before Datacamp, I was a data analyst at Etsy.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:40.279
That's where I got started on experimentation.

00:03:40.279 --> 00:03:43.240
So I worked on over 60 experiments with our search team.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:48.119
Etsy had been doing experimentations for over eight years at that point and running over

00:03:48.119 --> 00:03:50.479
500 experiments per year.

00:03:50.479 --> 00:03:54.899
To support all of this, Etsy had a big team of data engineers.

00:03:54.899 --> 00:03:58.679
So there were over five of them working full time on the data experimentation platform,

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:00.320
which Etsy had custom built.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:03.399
Over 1,000 metrics were computed for each experiment.

00:04:03.399 --> 00:04:07.259
There was a really nice UI that visualized all of this data so we could see things like

00:04:07.259 --> 00:04:12.039
confidence intervals, you know, power calculations for detecting 1% change.

00:04:12.039 --> 00:04:13.960
You can even customize that.

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:15.759
So this was really, really great.

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:20.040
And I come to Datacamp in April, and I know that part of my job is going to be helping

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:24.600
start experimentation at Datacamp, but I still felt a little bit like this in that first

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:25.600
couple weeks.

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:29.940
Now, to be very clear, especially for everyone at Datacamp who might be watching, I did not

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:33.559
lie on my resume, but here it was very different.

00:04:33.559 --> 00:04:37.200
There was no system for planning, analyzing, or presenting experiment results.

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:40.079
I think they'd only run about one or two tests before I joined.

00:04:40.119 --> 00:04:41.799
And there were no data engineers to build it.

00:04:41.799 --> 00:04:45.160
And again, that's partly why I was brought in as a data scientist, but this part would

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:46.399
be a bit new.

00:04:46.399 --> 00:04:49.459
And I want to share four lessons I learned along the way.

00:04:49.459 --> 00:04:53.440
The first is build tools to save yourself time.

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:57.399
Who here has ever had a first this, then that question?

00:04:57.399 --> 00:05:00.480
Something like who tried X, then did Y?

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:03.399
What percent of people who did X, then did Y?

00:05:03.399 --> 00:05:06.000
What was the last thing people did before doing Y?

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.059
Or what were all the things people did after doing X, right?

00:05:09.059 --> 00:05:11.179
So they can be, you know, structured differently.

00:05:11.179 --> 00:05:14.420
Maybe you're interested in all the behavior afterwards, just the first time.

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:18.100
But really, it's you have two sets of behaviors, and you want to follow one user and understand

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:20.779
what happened first this, then that.

00:05:20.779 --> 00:05:23.619
And this is the type of questions I would ask in A-B testing.

00:05:23.619 --> 00:05:26.619
Say what percentage of the people in the treatment first control registered?

00:05:26.619 --> 00:05:29.019
And this would be registered after starting the experiment.

00:05:29.019 --> 00:05:31.739
So I'd have experiment starts and registration.

00:05:31.739 --> 00:05:36.100
What were the ad clicks that had a course start within two days?

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:40.179
And my first attempt at doing this involved a lot of lengthy repetitive code.

00:05:40.179 --> 00:05:44.059
There was a ton of copying and pasting, and it was very hard to switch between different

00:05:44.059 --> 00:05:45.059
types of funnels.

00:05:45.059 --> 00:05:48.660
By which I mean switching between something like I want the first time they did this,

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:50.019
and then the first time they did that.

00:05:50.019 --> 00:05:53.660
I want the first time they did this, and everything they did after that.

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:56.579
It wasn't very easy to go between those types of funnels.

00:05:56.579 --> 00:06:01.079
And when you're doing repetitive tasks, you know, a lot of you may know here, it's time

00:06:01.079 --> 00:06:02.660
to write a function.

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:05.540
And in my case, a package.

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:11.179
Unfortunately, I faced a bit of an issue, which was this was me and writing packages.

00:06:11.179 --> 00:06:12.700
I sort of knew this was something.

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:17.179
I even had written a blog post a couple years ago that was like, you know, writing my first

00:06:17.179 --> 00:06:20.739
R package, part one, where I talk about how I'm going to write this R package.

00:06:20.739 --> 00:06:22.899
And there was never a part two.

00:06:22.899 --> 00:06:26.660
There actually still is not.

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:30.339
So you know, I was a little, you know, wasn't really sure what to do.

00:06:30.339 --> 00:06:33.940
But fortunately, I had David Robinson at data cam.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:34.940
Wait.

00:06:35.339 --> 00:06:36.660
Not that Dave Robinson.

00:06:36.660 --> 00:06:37.660
This one.

00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:38.660
You might see him walking around.

00:06:38.660 --> 00:06:39.660
Right?

00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:40.899
He's got the big widow peak.

00:06:40.899 --> 00:06:44.140
So Dave Robinson is our chief data scientist at data camp.

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:45.459
As I said, also my brother.

00:06:45.459 --> 00:06:47.540
And he is very experienced in writing packages.

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:53.179
So one day you set up a hackathon for him, me, and one of the other growth team members

00:06:53.179 --> 00:06:56.339
at data camp to write the package funnel join.

00:06:56.339 --> 00:06:59.220
And if you'd like to try it out yourself, it's available on GitHub.

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:03.980
And what funnel join is, it's goal is to make it easy to analyze behavior funnels.

00:07:04.019 --> 00:07:08.179
So I'm going to walk through how funnel join works.

00:07:08.179 --> 00:07:10.760
The structure of it is you start with two tables.

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:13.420
The first table is your first set of behaviors.

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:15.179
And then the second table is your second set.

00:07:15.179 --> 00:07:17.299
The one that you want to happen afterward.

00:07:17.299 --> 00:07:20.299
You tell it what the user column names are, because you want to be able to connect the

00:07:20.299 --> 00:07:22.140
user across tables.

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:23.660
You tell it what the time columns are.

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:28.179
Again, you want to make sure the time in the table on the left-hand side always has to

00:07:28.179 --> 00:07:30.220
be less than the time on the right-hand side.

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:31.899
It has to happen before.

00:07:31.899 --> 00:07:35.140
The type of after join, which I'm going to talk about a little bit more.

00:07:35.140 --> 00:07:36.380
And finally, the type of join.

00:07:36.380 --> 00:07:38.500
So like inner, left, right.

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:40.579
All the dplyr joins.

00:07:40.579 --> 00:07:43.420
So one example is a first any question.

00:07:43.420 --> 00:07:47.940
What are all the courses people started after visiting the home page for the first time?

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:50.140
So here I would write my funnel join.

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:53.299
I write an after inner join, so using the type inner.

00:07:53.299 --> 00:07:57.220
I specify in the type argument the first-any.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:59.700
And then I have my time columns and my user columns.

00:07:59.700 --> 00:08:03.660
And so I get out this table, and you'll see, just as we would hope, course started at is

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:05.100
always greater than viewed at.

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:11.059
So now I could say, oh, person three viewed the home page on June 6.

00:08:11.059 --> 00:08:14.779
And we have two entries for them, even for the same home page view, because they started

00:08:14.779 --> 00:08:15.779
two different courses.

00:08:15.779 --> 00:08:18.059
And that's because I did a first-any join.

00:08:18.059 --> 00:08:22.100
But if I wanted to switch it up and say what percent of people saw the pricing page for

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:25.660
the first time and then subscribed, I just changed the type of funnel.

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:27.459
So a very similar structure.

00:08:27.459 --> 00:08:29.779
Change type to first, first after.

00:08:29.779 --> 00:08:34.179
And now because it's a left join, we also have the NA at the subscribe dot.

00:08:34.179 --> 00:08:37.619
What if I want to say, well, that's great, but I really want a tight funnel.

00:08:37.619 --> 00:08:40.479
I want it to happen within four days.

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:42.299
I can add a max gap argument.

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:43.859
So I give it a diff time argument.

00:08:43.859 --> 00:08:48.539
And now if I ran the same code, we see a bit more NAs on the subscribe dot, because even

00:08:48.539 --> 00:08:53.739
though those people subscribed, they didn't do it within four days.

00:08:53.859 --> 00:08:55.940
As I said, there are many funnel types supported.

00:08:55.940 --> 00:09:01.580
So this last before, first after, any-any, first-any, supports all types of dplyr joins.

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:06.419
It works on remote tables, because it uses dplyr, so it takes advantage of dbplyr.

00:09:06.419 --> 00:09:09.739
And bug fixes, pull requests, feature requests, welcome.

00:09:09.739 --> 00:09:13.140
Please try it yourself and let me know how it goes.

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:17.099
So my second lesson is that everything that can go wrong will go wrong.

00:09:17.099 --> 00:09:20.159
A non-exhaustive list of things that have happened.

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:21.739
People are put in both control and treatment.

00:09:21.739 --> 00:09:22.739
That should not happen.

00:09:22.739 --> 00:09:24.059
You should get one experience.

00:09:24.059 --> 00:09:25.539
People in the experiment have no page views.

00:09:25.539 --> 00:09:28.340
They are mysterious users with only back-end events.

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:30.940
People have multiple experiment starts in the same group.

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:34.140
There aren't the same number of people in the control versus treatment.

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:36.460
Experiment starts didn't have cookies, so we couldn't even track the user.

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:39.500
We couldn't link that start to any other event.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:42.179
We realized here we really needed to check our assumptions.

00:09:42.179 --> 00:09:46.739
So we wrote up this doc of things we needed to do, because, again, these were all things

00:09:46.739 --> 00:09:48.140
we didn't initially think to check.

00:09:48.539 --> 00:09:50.739
If the system is working correctly, they should happen.

00:09:50.739 --> 00:09:54.539
When we started getting weird results, we dug into it, and we realized, oh, all these

00:09:54.539 --> 00:09:56.739
things are going wrong.

00:09:56.739 --> 00:10:00.700
My initial solution was, again, this kind of lengthy, repetitive code that I'd copy

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:05.780
between experiment files, you know, OK, this check, all these things.

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:10.179
But as a famous data scientist once said, when you've written the same code three times,

00:10:10.179 --> 00:10:11.179
write a function.

00:10:11.179 --> 00:10:14.340
When you've given the same in-person advice three times, write a blog post.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:18.859
And I'll add to that, when you've run the same process three times, make a dashboard.

00:10:18.859 --> 00:10:22.299
So I could have come up with a solution here, right, of, like, making another package.

00:10:22.299 --> 00:10:26.299
That's what we saw for the first problem was the solution to all this copy-pasting.

00:10:26.299 --> 00:10:29.460
But in this case, a dashboard is really what's going to be helpful.

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:32.940
And what it also did was it's building a tool that empowers others.

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:36.020
We've heard a lot today about how useful Shiny can be.

00:10:36.020 --> 00:10:40.619
If you saw the presentation at 11 a.m. this morning from Jacqueline and Heather Nolis

00:10:40.619 --> 00:10:44.900
on their work at T-Mobile, they talked about how putting a Shiny app in front of the stakeholders

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:48.460
so they could play with the machine learning model themselves is what got them the resources

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:50.739
to build out a whole team.

00:10:50.739 --> 00:10:53.739
So I built a Shiny app for showing our experiment data.

00:10:53.739 --> 00:10:55.280
I started with the health metrics.

00:10:55.280 --> 00:11:00.099
So now for every experiment, these are automatically calculated, and we can know if something's

00:11:00.099 --> 00:11:01.539
going wrong.

00:11:01.539 --> 00:11:02.539
It's color-coded.

00:11:02.539 --> 00:11:06.979
So we see that the duplicate cookies, cookies of multiple variation, things look good.

00:11:06.979 --> 00:11:08.059
It's green.

00:11:08.059 --> 00:11:09.940
Cookies with no page views is not looking as good.

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:11.179
It's yellow and red.

00:11:11.179 --> 00:11:14.859
And so then that can suggest what we might need to look into.

00:11:14.859 --> 00:11:16.419
We have a biometric view.

00:11:16.419 --> 00:11:21.580
So if you want to look for all the experiments that are running or even all time, how did

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:23.419
all of those affect chapter starts?

00:11:23.419 --> 00:11:27.140
We can see, all right, the control versus treatment, the percent change.

00:11:27.140 --> 00:11:31.460
Again, this color coding, which is a small thing, but it's nice because at a glance,

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:32.700
I know what to take from this.

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:35.219
All right, three experiments didn't have an impact.

00:11:35.219 --> 00:11:37.020
The fourth one had a negative impact.

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:41.859
And that will only show in red when the p-value is less than 0.05.

00:11:41.859 --> 00:11:45.299
We also have our nice confidence intervals, again, just for some more visualization and

00:11:45.299 --> 00:11:46.820
helping to understand these.

00:11:46.820 --> 00:11:49.640
We have an individual experiment view.

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:52.419
So now this shows the description and the hypothesis.

00:11:52.419 --> 00:11:56.859
Because as the experiment metrics grew, as we started tracking more, we went from like

00:11:56.859 --> 00:12:01.640
three to 11, it became a bit cumbersome to look just by metric when you're only interested

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:03.179
in one experiment.

00:12:03.179 --> 00:12:07.859
So again, all the information was there, but just making it easier for people to see at

00:12:07.859 --> 00:12:12.380
a glance and to have this individual experiment view.

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:16.299
And to level up a little bit, I would get a common request of what percent increase

00:12:16.299 --> 00:12:18.059
can we detect in a two-week test?

00:12:18.059 --> 00:12:20.080
And this is a really important question.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:24.219
Because otherwise, you may end up running tests, you know, say you have a great idea.

00:12:24.219 --> 00:12:29.340
I want to know, are we going to increase registrations by changing the color of a button?

00:12:29.340 --> 00:12:33.460
But if you run a power calculation, this will tell you, all right, in two weeks with

00:12:33.460 --> 00:12:37.580
the amount of people who are visiting, the amount of people who say register already,

00:12:37.580 --> 00:12:41.979
you would need a 50% increase in registrations to detect a change.

00:12:41.979 --> 00:12:44.260
So that probably means you don't want to run that test.

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:46.140
And I was really glad people were asking this question.

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:47.340
I encouraged them.

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:52.080
But could I make a tool so that people could answer this themselves without code?

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:57.659
So I wanted to go from delivering information to helping people discover information.

00:12:57.700 --> 00:13:03.179
And in the famous words of Barney Stinson, challenge accepted.

00:13:03.179 --> 00:13:04.820
We got the impact calculator.

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:10.340
So now anyone at Datacamp can enter URLs here and say they're interested in running an experiment

00:13:10.340 --> 00:13:11.340
on our homepage.

00:13:11.340 --> 00:13:15.919
They can say, all right, maybe I'm only interested in signed out users, maybe only mobile.

00:13:15.919 --> 00:13:19.260
And this table that you see will recalculate and say, all right, first, this is how many

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:22.179
unique users there are over a time period.

00:13:22.179 --> 00:13:26.140
This is what percent of them start a chapter, register, et cetera.

00:13:26.140 --> 00:13:29.539
So this is really great, because sometimes even just from this, you'll be like, oh, wow,

00:13:29.539 --> 00:13:32.900
I didn't realize these four URLs get so little traffic.

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:34.979
Probably doesn't make sense to run an experiment.

00:13:34.979 --> 00:13:38.419
But the second part is this has a power calculation table underneath it.

00:13:38.419 --> 00:13:41.380
So it will tell you the answer to this question.

00:13:41.380 --> 00:13:46.260
Of an 18 days, you'll be able to detect an increase of, say, 4% for chapter starts, 6.5%

00:13:46.260 --> 00:13:48.099
for registrations.

00:13:48.099 --> 00:13:51.739
And it's always a bit of a guessing game of what impact your test will have.

00:13:51.739 --> 00:13:54.859
But usually you'll have some sort of idea of what's reasonable.

00:13:54.859 --> 00:13:55.859
And so they could look at this.

00:13:55.859 --> 00:13:59.900
They could say, all right, well, maybe if I do both desktop and mobile, is that going

00:13:59.900 --> 00:14:04.580
to get me down to 3% if I make it 25 days instead?

00:14:04.580 --> 00:14:09.200
And they could iterate really quickly without ever having to come to me.

00:14:09.200 --> 00:14:14.500
And my final thing that I learned was to make it easy to do the right thing.

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:19.179
One best practice for A-B tests is to have a single key metric per experiment.

00:14:19.179 --> 00:14:20.940
It helps clarify decision making.

00:14:20.940 --> 00:14:24.580
Because if you have multiple metrics and one goes up and one goes down, you could be left

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:28.419
not really knowing what you should do in that situation.

00:14:28.419 --> 00:14:30.520
It also allows you to run that power analysis.

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:33.380
So for a power analysis to be run, you need to have the metric.

00:14:33.380 --> 00:14:34.539
You need to know its rate.

00:14:34.539 --> 00:14:38.159
And that can tell you how long to run the experiment for.

00:14:38.159 --> 00:14:39.159
So it's great.

00:14:39.159 --> 00:14:44.099
And I really am doing a lot to educate people at Datacamp about A-B testing best practices.

00:14:44.099 --> 00:14:49.020
But even more than that, building it into the process and making it easy for people.

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:52.179
So this is our air table where we put the information about our experiments.

00:14:52.179 --> 00:14:54.619
And you can see at the top here is a success metric.

00:14:54.619 --> 00:14:57.460
And so each experiment is required to have one.

00:14:57.460 --> 00:14:58.460
And only one.

00:14:58.460 --> 00:15:00.940
We can write in the notes maybe other things we care about.

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:03.219
But this is the key metric.

00:15:03.219 --> 00:15:07.380
And then we can show� you know, then that forces people to make a decision.

00:15:07.380 --> 00:15:10.219
We can match that to something on the dashboard.

00:15:10.219 --> 00:15:14.179
And it can help make decision making at the end a lot easier.

00:15:14.179 --> 00:15:17.500
Second guideline is to run the experiment for the length you've planned on.

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:23.340
This is a graph showing about how� if you simulate thousands of null experiments and

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:27.580
you checked every day if the P value was less than .05 and you stopped your experiment at

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:32.099
that point, you'd get an over 20% false positive rate.

00:15:32.099 --> 00:15:34.460
So a huge increase.

00:15:34.460 --> 00:15:39.020
You really want to do that power analysis, set the time of your experiment, and stick

00:15:39.020 --> 00:15:40.780
to it.

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:44.140
That's why we added to the health checks metric a start date and an end date for experiments.

00:15:44.380 --> 00:15:48.780
Again, it could be really tempting for a stakeholder to message me, hey, I saw� I checked this

00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:51.140
dashboard on the individual experiment.

00:15:51.140 --> 00:15:52.140
This metric went up.

00:15:52.140 --> 00:15:54.700
Why don't we just go ahead and launch it?

00:15:54.700 --> 00:15:58.179
But now they say, okay, I see the end date is not for another couple days.

00:15:58.179 --> 00:16:02.260
I know I'm supposed to follow this best practice, so I will do it.

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:06.700
So in conclusion, to recap, build tools to save yourself time.

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:07.739
That's where funnel join came out.

00:16:07.739 --> 00:16:11.380
If you're finding yourself doing something over and over again, it's really worthwhile

00:16:11.380 --> 00:16:13.500
to invest some time in making it easier.

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:17.020
And it also means the other thing we found is that now a lot of analyses we wouldn't

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:20.460
have really started before because they'd be a bit cumbersome.

00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:24.099
We have funnel join in our back pocket, and that can help us� we know we can do it really

00:16:24.099 --> 00:16:27.760
quickly and it enables us to do some more work.

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:29.299
Everything that can go wrong will go wrong.

00:16:29.299 --> 00:16:33.179
You have to check your assumptions and build systems to do that.

00:16:33.179 --> 00:16:37.299
Build tools that empower others, especially, I found, effective dashboards.

00:16:37.299 --> 00:16:40.219
And finally, make it easy to do the right thing.

00:16:40.219 --> 00:16:44.979
It's great to put in work educating others, maybe some rules to follow, but the easier

00:16:44.979 --> 00:16:49.099
you can make it for them to follow the best practice, the more likely you'll get the result

00:16:49.099 --> 00:16:50.619
you want.

00:16:50.619 --> 00:16:54.780
Many thanks to the growth and data science teams at Datacamp, especially David Robinson

00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:57.979
and Anthony Baker, who are co-authors of funnel join.

00:16:57.979 --> 00:17:02.419
The analytics and data engineering team at Etsy, where I was first a data analyst.

00:17:02.419 --> 00:17:05.020
And with that, thank you very much, and I'm happy to take questions.

00:17:11.219 --> 00:17:15.219
Anybody got a question?

00:17:23.219 --> 00:17:27.219
Here we go.

00:17:27.219 --> 00:17:28.859
Thanks for putting this together.

00:17:28.859 --> 00:17:32.219
Any words of caution before we rely on your package on our own work?

00:17:32.219 --> 00:17:34.099
Yeah, so it's funny.

00:17:34.099 --> 00:17:39.260
When I gave this talk for the first time back in October, November, there was a big caution

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:42.619
sign that was like, still in beta.

00:17:42.619 --> 00:17:47.140
The only thing I would say is actually, there's some issues.

00:17:47.140 --> 00:17:50.339
It hasn't been tested on non-postgres remote tables.

00:17:50.339 --> 00:17:54.560
I don't think it would give you the wrong answer so much as not work.

00:17:54.560 --> 00:18:00.459
Some other behaviors we know, like there's a bug sometimes when you do multiple after

00:18:00.459 --> 00:18:03.260
joins remotely, but now we don't enable you to do that.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:04.619
We basically throw an error.

00:18:04.619 --> 00:18:07.099
So we've really tried where we can to throw errors.

00:18:07.099 --> 00:18:09.979
That being said, we use it very extensively at Datacamp.

00:18:09.979 --> 00:18:11.739
It's built with Travis CI.

00:18:11.739 --> 00:18:14.780
There's a bunch of tests we have, but definitely try it out.

00:18:14.780 --> 00:18:18.500
But if something looks a little wacky, always double check a bit, but we found it generally

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:19.140
works pretty well.

